53 //========================================================================
54 /// A Generalised Element class.
55 ///
56 /// The main components of a GeneralisedElement are:
57 /// - pointers to its internal and external Data, which are stored together
58 /// in a single array so that we need only store one pointer.
59 /// The internal Data are placed at the beginning
60 /// of the array and the external Data are stored at the end.
61 /// - a pointer to a global Time
62 /// - a lookup table that establishes the relation between local
63 /// and global equation numbers.
64 ///
65 /// We also provide interfaces for functions that compute the
66 /// element's Jacobian matrix and/or the Vector of residuals.
67 /// In addition, an interface that returns a mass matrix --- the matrix
68 /// of terms that multiply any time derivatives in the problem --- is
69 /// also provided to permit explicit time-stepping and the solution
70 /// of the generalised eigenproblems.
71 //========================================================================
72 class GeneralisedElement
73 {
74 private:
75 /// Storage for the global equation numbers represented by the
76 /// degrees of freedom in the element.
77 unsigned long* Eqn_number;
78
79 /// Storage for array of pointers to degrees of freedom ordered
80 /// by local equation number. This information is not needed, except in
81 /// continuation, bifurcation tracking and periodic orbit calculations.
82 /// It is not set up unless the control flag
83 /// Problem::Store_local_dof_pts_in_elements = true
84 double** Dof_pt;
85
86 /// Storage for pointers to internal and external data.
87 /// The data is of the same type and so can be addressed by
88 /// a single pointer. The idea is that the array is of
89 /// total size Ninternal_data + Nexternal_data.
90 /// The internal data are stored at the beginning of the array
91 /// and the external data are stored at the end of the array.
92 Data** Data_pt;
93
94 /// Pointer to array storage for local equation numbers associated
95 /// with internal and external data. Again, we save storage by using
96 /// a single pointer to access this information. The first index of the
97 /// array is of dimension Nineternal_data + Nexternal_data and the second
98 /// index varies with the number of values stored at the data object.
99 /// In the most general case, however, the scheme is as memory efficient
100 /// as possible.
101 int** Data_local_eqn;
102
103 /// Number of degrees of freedom
104 unsigned Ndof;
105
106 /// Number of internal data
107 unsigned Ninternal_data;
108
109 /// Number of external data
110 unsigned Nexternal_data;
111
112 /// Storage for boolean flags of size Ninternal_data + Nexternal_data
113 /// that correspond to the data used in the element. The flags
114 /// indicate whether the particular
115 /// internal or external data should be included in the general
116 /// finite-difference loop in fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd() or
117 /// fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(). The default is that all
118 /// data WILL be included in the finite-difference loop, but in many
119 /// circumstances it is possible to treat certain (external) data
120 /// analytically. The use of an STL vector is optimal for memory
121 /// use because the booleans are represented as single-bits.
122 std::vector<bool> Data_fd;
123
124 protected:
125#ifdef OOMPH_HAS_MPI
126
127 /// Non-halo processor ID for Data; -1 if it's not a halo.
128 int Non_halo_proc_ID;
129
130 /// Does this element need to be kept as a halo element during a distribute?
131 bool Must_be_kept_as_halo;
132
133#endif
134
135 /// Add a (pointer to an) internal data object to the element and
136 /// return the index required to obtain it from the access
137 /// function \c internal_data_pt(). The boolean indicates whether
138 /// the datum should be included in the general finite-difference loop
139 /// when calculating the jacobian. The default value is true, i.e.
140 /// the data will be included in the finite differencing.
141 unsigned add_internal_data(Data* const& data_pt, const bool& fd = true);
142

144 /// Return the status of the boolean flag indicating whether
145 /// the internal data is included in the finite difference loop
146 inline bool internal_data_fd(const unsigned& i) const
147 {
148#ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
149 if (i >= Ninternal_data)
150 {
151 std::ostringstream error_message;
152 error_message << "Range Error: Internal data " << i
153 << " is not in the range (0," << Ninternal_data - 1
154 << ")";
155 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
156 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
157 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
158 }
159#endif
160 // Return the value
161 return Data_fd[i];
162 }

200#endif

203 }

206 /// and pointers to dofs (if stored)

212 Dof_pt = 0;
213 Ndof = 0;

233 /// Assign the local equation numbers for the internal
234 /// and external Data
235 /// This must be called after the global equation numbers have all been
236 /// assigned. It is virtual so that it can be overloaded by
237 /// ElementWithExternalElements so that any external data from the
238 /// external elements in included in the numbering scheme.
239 /// If the boolean argument is true then pointers to the dofs will be
240 /// stored in Dof_pt
241 virtual void assign_internal_and_external_local_eqn_numbers(
242 const bool& store_local_dof_pt);
243
244 /// Assign all the local equation numbering schemes that can
245 /// be applied generically for the element. In most cases, this is the
246 /// function that will be overloaded by inherited classes. It is required
247 /// to ensure that assign_additional_local_eqn_numbers() can always be
248 /// called after ALL other local equation numbering has been performed.
249 /// The default for the GeneralisedElement is simply to call internal
250 /// and external local equation numbering.
251 /// If the boolean argument is true then pointers to the dofs will be stored
252 /// in Dof_pt
253 virtual inline void assign_all_generic_local_eqn_numbers(
254 const bool& store_local_dof_pt)
255 {
256 this->assign_internal_and_external_local_eqn_numbers(store_local_dof_pt);
257 }

259 /// Setup any additional look-up schemes for local equation numbers.
260 /// Examples of use include using local storage to refer to explicit
261 /// degrees of freedom. The additional memory cost of such storage may
262 /// or may not be offset by fast local access.
263 virtual void assign_additional_local_eqn_numbers() {}

265 /// Return the local equation number corresponding to the j-th
266 /// value stored at the i-th internal data
267 inline int internal_local_eqn(const unsigned& i, const unsigned& j) const
268 {
269#ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
270 if (i >= Ninternal_data)
271 {
272 std::ostringstream error_message;
273 error_message << "Range Error: Internal data " << i
274 << " is not in the range (0," << Ninternal_data - 1
275 << ")";
276 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
277 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
278 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
279 }
280 else
281 {
282 unsigned n_value = internal_data_pt(i)->nvalue();
283 if (j >= n_value)
284 {
285 std::ostringstream error_message;
286 error_message << "Range Error: value " << j << " at internal data "
287 << i << " is not in the range (0," << n_value - 1
288 << ")";
289 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
290 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
291 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
292 }
293 }
294#endif
295 // Check that the data has been allocated
296#ifdef PARANOID
297 if (Data_local_eqn == 0)
298 {
299 throw OomphLibError(
300 "Internal local equation numbers have not been allocated",
301 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
302 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
303 }
304#endif
305 // Return the local equation number as stored in the Data_local_eqn array
306 return Data_local_eqn[i][j];
307 }
308
309 /// Return the local equation number corresponding to the j-th
310 /// value stored at the i-th external data
311 inline int external_local_eqn(const unsigned& i, const unsigned& j)
312 {
313 // Check that the data has been allocated
314#ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
315 if (i >= Nexternal_data)
316 {
317 std::ostringstream error_message;
318 error_message << "Range Error: External data " << i
319 << " is not in the range (0," << Nexternal_data - 1
320 << ")";
321 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
322 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
323 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
324 }
325 else
326 {
327 unsigned n_value = external_data_pt(i)->nvalue();
328 if (j >= n_value)
329 {
330 std::ostringstream error_message;
331 error_message << "Range Error: value " << j << " at internal data "
332 << i << " is not in the range (0," << n_value - 1
333 << ")";
334 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
335 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
336 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
337 }
338 }
339#endif
340#ifdef PARANOID
341 if (Data_local_eqn == 0)
342 {
343 throw OomphLibError(
344 "External local equation numbers have not been allocated",
345 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
346 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
347 }
348#endif
349 // Return the local equation number stored as the j-th value of the
350 // i-th external data object.
351 return Data_local_eqn[Ninternal_data + i][j];
352 }

354 /// Add the elemental contribution to the residuals vector. Note that
355 /// this function will NOT initialise the residuals vector. It must be
356 /// called after the residuals vector has been initialised to zero.
357 virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(Vector<double>& residuals)
358 {
359 std::string error_message =
360 "Empty fill_in_contribution_to_residuals() has been called.\n";
361 error_message +=
362 "This function is called from the default implementations of\n";
363 error_message += "get_residuals() and get_jacobian();\n";
364 error_message +=
365 "and must calculate the residuals vector without initialising any of ";
366 error_message += "its entries.\n\n";
367
368 error_message +=
369 "If you do not wish to use these defaults, you must overload both\n";
370 error_message += "get_residuals() and get_jacobian(), which must "
371 "initialise the entries\n";
372 error_message += "of the residuals vector and jacobian matrix to zero.\n";
373
374 error_message += "N.B. the default get_jacobian() function employs "
375 "finite differencing\n";
376
377 throw OomphLibError(
378 error_message, OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION, OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
379 }
380
381 /// Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the internal
382 /// degrees of freedom using finite differences.
383 /// This version of the function assumes that the residuals vector has
384 /// already been calculated. If the boolean argument is true, the finite
385 /// differencing will be performed for all internal data, irrespective of
386 /// the information in Data_fd. The default value (false)
387 /// uses the information in Data_fd to selectively difference only
388 /// certain data.
389 void fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(Vector<double>& residuals,
390 DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian,
391 const bool& fd_all_data = false);
392
393 /// Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the internal
394 /// degrees of freedom using finite differences. This version computes
395 /// the residuals vector before calculating the jacobian terms.
396 /// If the boolean argument is true, the finite
397 /// differencing will be performed for all internal data, irrespective of
398 /// the information in Data_fd. The default value (false)
399 /// uses the information in Data_fd to selectively difference only
400 /// certain data.
401 void fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian,
402 const bool& fd_all_data = false)
403 {
404 // Allocate storage for the residuals
405 Vector<double> residuals(Ndof, 0.0);
406 // Get the residuals for the entire element
407 get_residuals(residuals);
408 // Call the jacobian calculation
409 fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(residuals, jacobian, fd_all_data);
410 }
411
412
413 /// Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the external
414 /// degrees of freedom using finite differences.
415 /// This version of the function assumes that the residuals vector has
416 /// already been calculated.
417 /// If the boolean argument is true, the finite
418 /// differencing will be performed for all external data, irrespective of
419 /// the information in Data_fd. The default value (false)
420 /// uses the information in Data_fd to selectively difference only
421 /// certain data.
422 void fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(Vector<double>& residuals,
423 DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian,
424 const bool& fd_all_data = false);
425
426
427 /// Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the external
428 /// degrees of freedom using finite differences. This version computes
429 /// the residuals vector before calculating the jacobian terms.
430 /// If the boolean argument is true, the finite
431 /// differencing will be performed for all internal data, irrespective of
432 /// the information in Data_fd. The default value (false)
433 /// uses the information in Data_fd to selectively difference only
434 /// certain data.
435 void fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian,
436 const bool& fd_all_data = false)
437 {
438 // Allocate storage for a residuals vector
439 Vector<double> residuals(Ndof);
440 // Get the residuals for the entire element
441 get_residuals(residuals);
442 // Call the jacobian calculation
443 fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(residuals, jacobian, fd_all_data);
444 }

493 /// Add the elemental contribution to the jacobian matrix.
494 /// and the residuals vector. Note that
495 /// this function will NOT initialise the residuals vector or the jacobian
496 /// matrix. It must be called after the residuals vector and
497 /// jacobian matrix have been initialised to zero. The default
498 /// is to use finite differences to calculate the jacobian
499 virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian(Vector<double>& residuals,
500 DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian)
501 {
502 // Add the contribution to the residuals
503 fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(residuals);
504 // Allocate storage for the full residuals (residuals of entire element)
505 Vector<double> full_residuals(Ndof);
506 // Get the residuals for the entire element
507 get_residuals(full_residuals);
508 // Calculate the contributions from the internal dofs
509 //(finite-difference the lot by default)
510 fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(full_residuals, jacobian, true);
511 // Calculate the contributions from the external dofs
512 //(finite-difference the lot by default)
513 fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(full_residuals, jacobian, true);
514 }

702 /// Return the global equation number corresponding to the
703 /// ieqn_local-th local equation number
704 unsigned long eqn_number(const unsigned& ieqn_local) const
705 {
706#ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
707 if (ieqn_local >= Ndof)
708 {
709 std::ostringstream error_message;
710 error_message << "Range Error: Equation number " << ieqn_local
711 << " is not in the range (0," << Ndof - 1 << ")";
712 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
713 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
714 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
715 }
716#endif
717 return Eqn_number[ieqn_local];
718 }

721 /// Return the local equation number corresponding to the
722 /// ieqn_global-th global equation number. Returns minus one (-1) if there
723 /// is
724 /// no local degree of freedom corresponding to the chosen global equation
725 /// number
726 int local_eqn_number(const unsigned long& ieqn_global) const
727 {
728 // Cache the number of degrees of freedom in the element
729 const unsigned n_dof = this->Ndof;
730 // Loop over the local equation numbers
731 for (unsigned n = 0; n < n_dof; n++)
732 {
733 // If the global equation numbers match return
734 if (ieqn_global == Eqn_number[n])
735 {
736 return n;
737 }
738 }
739
740 // If we've got all the way to the end the number has not been found
741 // return minus one.
742 return -1;
743 }

976 /// Calculate the vector of residuals of the equations in the
977 /// element. By default initialise the vector to zero and then call the
978 /// fill_in_contribution_to_residuals() function. Note that this entire
979 /// function can be overloaded if desired.
980 virtual void get_residuals(Vector<double>& residuals)
981 {
982 // Zero the residuals vector
983 residuals.initialise(0.0);
984 // Add the elemental contribution to the residuals vector
985 fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(residuals);
986 }

988 /// Calculate the elemental Jacobian matrix "d equation / d
989 /// variable".
990 virtual void get_jacobian(Vector<double>& residuals,
991 DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian)
992 {
993 // Zero the residuals vector
994 residuals.initialise(0.0);
995 // Zero the jacobian matrix
996 jacobian.initialise(0.0);
997 // Add the elemental contribution to the residuals vector
998 fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian(residuals, jacobian);
999 }

1001 /// Calculate the residuals and the elemental "mass" matrix, the
1002 /// matrix that multiplies the time derivative terms in a problem.
1003 virtual void get_mass_matrix(Vector<double>& residuals,
1004 DenseMatrix<double>& mass_matrix)
1005 {
1006 // Zero the residuals vector
1007 residuals.initialise(0.0);
1008 // Zero the mass matrix
1009 mass_matrix.initialise(0.0);
1010 // Add the elemental contribution to the vector and matrix
1011 fill_in_contribution_to_mass_matrix(residuals, mass_matrix);
1012 }
1013
1014 /// Calculate the residuals and jacobian and elemental "mass" matrix,
1015 /// the matrix that multiplies the time derivative terms.
1016 virtual void get_jacobian_and_mass_matrix(Vector<double>& residuals,
1017 DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian,
1018 DenseMatrix<double>& mass_matrix)
1019 {
1020 // Zero the residuals vector
1021 residuals.initialise(0.0);
1022 // Zero the jacobian matrix
1023 jacobian.initialise(0.0);
1024 // Zero the mass matrix
1025 mass_matrix.initialise(0.0);
1026 // Add the elemental contribution to the vector and matrix
1027 fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian_and_mass_matrix(
1028 residuals, jacobian, mass_matrix);
1029 }

1296 //========================================================================
1297 /// A general Finite Element class.
1298 ///
1299 /// The main components of a FiniteElement are:
1300 /// - pointers to its Nodes
1301 /// - pointers to its internal Data (inherited from GeneralisedElement)
1302 /// - pointers to its external Data (inherited from GeneralisedElement)
1303 /// - a pointer to a spatial integration scheme
1304 /// - a pointer to the global Time object (inherited from GeneralisedElement)
1305 /// - a lookup table which establishes the relation between local
1306 /// and global equation numbers (inherited from GeneralisedElement)
1307 ///
1308 /// We also provide interfaces for functions that compute the
1309 /// element's Jacobian matrix and/or the Vector of residuals
1310 /// (inherited from GeneralisedElement) plus various output routines.
1311 //========================================================================
1312 class FiniteElement : public virtual GeneralisedElement, public GeomObject
1313 {
1314 private:
1315 /// Pointer to the spatial integration scheme
1316 Integral* Integral_pt;
1317
1318 /// Storage for pointers to the nodes in the element
1319 Node** Node_pt;
1320
1321 /// Storage for the local equation numbers associated with
1322 /// the values stored at the nodes
1323 int** Nodal_local_eqn;
1324
1325 /// Number of nodes in the element
1326 unsigned Nnode;
1327
1328 /// The spatial dimension of the element, i.e. the number
1329 /// of local coordinates used to parametrize it.
1330 unsigned Elemental_dimension;
1331
1332 /// The spatial dimension of the nodes in the element.
1333 /// We assume that nodes have the same spatial dimension, because
1334 /// we cannot think of any "real" problems for which that would not
1335 /// be the case.
1336 unsigned Nodal_dimension;
1337
1338 /// The number of coordinate types required to interpolate
1339 /// the element's geometry between the nodes. For Lagrange elements
1340 /// it is 1 (the default). It must be over-ridden by using
1341 /// the set_nposition_type() function in the constructors of elements
1342 /// that use generalised coordinate, e.g. for 1D Hermite elements
1343 /// Nnodal_position_types =2.
1344 unsigned Nnodal_position_type;
1345
1346 protected:
1347 /// Assemble the jacobian matrix for the mapping from local
1348 /// to Eulerian coordinates, given the derivatives of the shape function
1349 /// w.r.t the local coordinates.
1350 virtual void assemble_local_to_eulerian_jacobian(
1351 const DShape& dpsids, DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian) const;
1352
1353 /// Assemble the the "jacobian" matrix of second derivatives of the
1354 /// mapping from local to Eulerian coordinates, given
1355 /// the second derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t. local coordinates.
1356 virtual void assemble_local_to_eulerian_jacobian2(

1402 /// Set the number of nodes in the element to n, by resizing

1405 {
1406 // This should only be done once, in a Node constructor
1407 //#ifdef PARANOID
1408 // if(Node_pt)
1409 // {

1430 /// Return the local equation number corresponding to the i-th
1431 /// value at the n-th local node.
1432 inline int nodal_local_eqn(const unsigned& n, const unsigned& i) const
1433 {
1434#ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
1435 if (n >= Nnode)
1436 {
1437 std::ostringstream error_message;
1438 error_message << "Range Error: Node number " << n
1439 << " is not in the range (0," << Nnode - 1 << ")";
1440 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
1441 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
1442 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
1443 }
1444 else
1445 {
1446 unsigned n_value = node_pt(n)->nvalue();
1447 if (i >= n_value)
1448 {
1449 std::ostringstream error_message;
1450 error_message << "Range Error: value " << i << " at node " << n
1451 << " is not in the range (0," << n_value - 1 << ")";
1452 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
1453 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
1454 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
1455 }
1456 }
1457#endif
1458#ifdef PARANOID
1459 // Check that the equations have been allocated
1460 if (Nodal_local_eqn == 0)
1461 {
1462 throw OomphLibError(
1463 "Nodal local equation numbers have not been allocated",
1464 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
1465 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
1466 }
1467#endif
1468 return Nodal_local_eqn[n][i];
1469 }

1570 /// A template-free interface that calculates the derivative w.r.t.

1574 /// \f[

1585 /// By default the function will use the dimension of the element to call
1586 /// the correct d_dshape_eulerian_dnodal_coordinates_templated_helper(..)

1697 /// Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the nodal
1698 /// degrees of freedom using finite differences. This version computes
1699 /// the residuals vector before calculating the jacobian terms.
1700 void fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian)
1701 {
1702 // Allocate storage for a residuals vector and initialise to zero
1703 unsigned n_dof = ndof();
1704 Vector<double> residuals(n_dof, 0.0);
1705 // Get the residuals for the entire element
1706 get_residuals(residuals);
1707 // Call the jacobian calculation
1708 fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(residuals, jacobian);
1709 }

1734 /// Add the elemental contribution to the jacobian matrix.
1735 /// and the residuals vector. Note that
1736 /// this function will NOT initialise the residuals vector or the jacobian
1737 /// matrix. It must be called after the residuals vector and
1738 /// jacobian matrix have been initialised to zero. The default
1739 /// is to use finite differences to calculate the jacobian
1740 void fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian(Vector<double>& residuals,
1741 DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian)
1742 {
1743 // Add the contribution to the residuals
1744 fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(residuals);
1745 // Allocate storage for the full residuals (residuals of entire element)
1746 unsigned n_dof = ndof();
1747 Vector<double> full_residuals(n_dof);
1748 // Get the residuals for the entire element
1749 get_residuals(full_residuals);
1750 // Calculate the contributions from the internal dofs
1751 //(finite-difference the lot by default)
1752 fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(full_residuals, jacobian, true);
1753 // Calculate the contributions from the external dofs
1754 //(finite-difference the lot by default)
1755 fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(full_residuals, jacobian, true);
1756 // Calculate the contributions from the nodal dofs
1757 fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(full_residuals, jacobian);
1758 }

1905 /// Global coordinates as function of local coordinates
1906 /// at previous time "level" t (t=0: present; t>0: previous).
1907 /// Either via FE representation of QElement or
1908 /// via macro-element (if Macro_elem_pt!=0).
1909 void get_x(const unsigned& t, const Vector<double>& s, Vector<double>& x)
1910 {
1911 // Get timestepper from first node
1912 TimeStepper* time_stepper_pt = node_pt(0)->time_stepper_pt();
1913
1914 // Number of previous values
1915 const unsigned nprev = time_stepper_pt->nprev_values();
1916
1917 // If t > nprev_values(), we're not dealing with a previous value
1918 // but a generalised history value -- this cannot be recovered from
1919 // macro element but must be determined by finite element interpolation
1920
1921 // If there is no macro element, or we're dealing with a generalised
1922 // history value then use the FE representation
1923 if ((Macro_elem_pt == 0) || (t > nprev))
1924 {
1925 interpolated_x(t, s, x);
1926 }
1927 // Otherwise use the macro element representation
1928 else
1929 {
1930 get_x_from_macro_element(t, s, x);
1931 }
1932 }

2400 /// This is an empty function that establishes a uniform
2401 /// interface for all (derived) elements that involve time-derivatives.
2402 /// Such elements are/should be implemented in ALE form to allow
2403 /// mesh motions. The additional expense associated with the
2404 /// computation of the mesh velocities is, of course, superfluous
2405 /// if the elements are used in problems in which the mesh is
2406 /// stationary. This function should therefore be overloaded
2407 /// in all derived elements that are formulated in ALE form
2408 /// to suppress the computation of the mesh velocities.
2409 /// The user disables the ALE functionality at his/her own risk!
2410 /// If the mesh does move after all, then the results will be wrong.
2411 /// Here we simply issue a warning message stating that the empty
2412 /// function has been called.
2413 virtual void disable_ALE()
2414 {
2415 std::ostringstream warn_message;
2416 warn_message
2417 << "Warning: You have just called the default (empty) function \n\n"
2418 << " FiniteElement::disable_ALE() \n\n"
2419 << "This suggests that you've either tried to call it for an element\n"
2420 << "that \n"
2421 << "(1) does not involve time-derivatives (e.g. a Poisson element) \n"
2422 << "(2) an element for which the time-derivatives aren't implemented \n"
2423 << " in ALE form \n"
2424 << "(3) an element for which the ALE form of the equations can't be \n"
2425 << " be disabled (yet).\n";
2426 OomphLibWarning(
2427 warn_message.str(), "Problem::disable_ALE()", OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
2428 }

2433 /// and simply establishes a common interface for all derived

2435 virtual void enable_ALE()
2436 {
2437 std::ostringstream warn_message;
2438 warn_message
2439 << "Warning: You have just called the default (empty) function \n\n"

2441 << "This suggests that you've either tried to call it for an element\n"

2443 << "(1) does not involve time-derivatives (e.g. a Poisson element) \n"
2444 << "(2) an element for which the time-derivatives aren't implemented \n"

2446 << "(3) an element for which the ALE form of the equations can't be \n"

2892 /// Paraview output -- this outputs the coordinates at the plot
2893 /// points (for parameter nplot) to specified output file.
2894 void output_paraview(std::ofstream& file_out, const unsigned& nplot) const
2895 {
2896 // Decide the dimensions of the nodes
2897 unsigned nnod = nnode();
2898 if (nnod == 0) return;
2899 unsigned n = node_pt(0)->ndim();
2900
2901 // Vector for local coordinates
2902 Vector<double> s(n, 0.0);
2903
2904 // Vector for cartesian coordinates
2905 Vector<double> x(n, 0.0);
2906
2907 // Determine the total number of plotpoints
2908 unsigned plot = nplot_points_paraview(nplot);
2909
2910 // Loop over the local points
2911 for (unsigned j = 0; j < plot; j++)
2912 {
2913 // Determine where in the local element the point is
2914 this->get_s_plot(j, nplot, s);
2915
2916 // Update the cartesian coordinates vector
2917 this->interpolated_x(s, x);
2918
2919 // Print the global coordinates. Note: no whitespace after last
2920 // coordinate or paraview is very unhappy.
2921 for (unsigned i = 0; i < n - 1; i++)
2922 {
2923 file_out << x[i] << " ";
2924 }
2925 file_out << x[n - 1];
2926
2927 // Since unstructured grid always needs 3 components for each
2928 // point, output 0's by default
2929 switch (n)
2930 {
2931 case 1:
2932 file_out << " 0"
2933 << " 0" << std::endl;
2934 break;
2935
2936 case 2:
2937 file_out << " 0" << std::endl;
2938 break;
2939
2940 case 3:
2941 file_out << std::endl;
2942 break;
2943
2944 // Paraview can't handle more than 3 dimensions, output error
2945 default:
2946 throw OomphLibError(
2947 "Printing PlotPoint to .vtu failed; it has >3 dimensions.",
2948 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
2949 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
2950 }
2951 }
2952 }

3545 //============================================================================
3546 /// SolidFiniteElement class.
3547 ///
3548 /// Solid elements are elements whose nodal positions are unknowns
3549 /// in the problem -- their nodes are SolidNodes. In such elements,
3550 /// the nodes not only have a variable (Eulerian) but also a fixed
3551 /// (Lagrangian) position. The positional variables have their own
3552 /// local equation numbering scheme which is set up with
3553 /// \code assign_solid_local_eqn_numbers () \endcode
3554 /// The derivatives of the
3555 /// `solid equations' (i.e. the equations that determine the
3556 /// nodal positions) with respect to the nodal positions, required
3557 /// in the Jacobian matrix, are determined by finite differencing.
3558 ///
3559 /// In the present form, the SolidFiniteElement represents
3560 /// a fully functional base class for `proper' solid mechanics elements,
3561 /// but it can also be combined
3562 /// (via inheritance) with elements that solve additional equations.
3563 /// This is particularly useful in cases where the solid equations
3564 /// are merely used to update the nodal positions in a moving mesh
3565 /// problem, although this can prove costly in practice.
3566 //============================================================================
3567 class SolidFiniteElement : public virtual FiniteElement
3568 {
3569 public:
3570 /// Set the lagrangian dimension of the element --- the number
3571 /// of lagrangian coordinates stored at the nodes in the element.
3572 void set_lagrangian_dimension(const unsigned& lagrangian_dimension)
3573 {
3574 Lagrangian_dimension = lagrangian_dimension;
3575 }
3576
3577 /// Return whether there is internal solid data (e.g. discontinuous
3578 /// solid pressure). At present, this is used to report an error in
3579 /// setting initial conditions for ElasticProblems which can't
3580 /// handle such cases. The default is false.
3581 virtual bool has_internal_solid_data()
3582 {
3583 return false;
3584 }
3585
3586 /// Pointer to function that computes the "multiplier" for the
3587 /// inertia terms in the consistent determination of the initial
3588 /// conditions for Newmark timestepping.
3589 typedef double (*MultiplierFctPt)(const Vector<double>& xi);
3590
3591 /// Constructor: Set defaults
3592 SolidFiniteElement()
3593 : FiniteElement(),
3594 Undeformed_macro_elem_pt(0),
3595 Solid_ic_pt(0),
3596 Multiplier_fct_pt(0),
3597 Position_local_eqn(0),
3598 Lagrangian_dimension(0),
3599 Nnodal_lagrangian_type(1),
3600 Solve_for_consistent_newmark_accel_flag(false)
3601 {
3602 }
3603
3604 /// Destructor to clean up any allocated memory
3605 virtual ~SolidFiniteElement();
3606
3607 /// Broken copy constructor
3608 SolidFiniteElement(const SolidFiniteElement&) = delete;

3611 /*void operator=(const SolidFiniteElement&) = delete;*/

3613 /// The number of geometric data affecting a SolidFiniteElemnet is
3614 /// the same as the number of nodes (one variable position data per node)
3615 inline unsigned ngeom_data() const
3616 {
3617 return nnode();
3618 }
3619
3620 /// Return pointer to the j-th Data item that the object's
3621 /// shape depends on. (Redirects to the nodes' positional Data).
3622 inline Data* geom_data_pt(const unsigned& j)
3623 {
3624 return static_cast<SolidNode*>(node_pt(j))->variable_position_pt();
3625 }
3626
3627 /// Specify Data that affects the geometry of the element
3628 /// by adding the position Data to the set that's passed in.
3629 /// (This functionality is required in FSI problems; set is used to
3630 /// avoid double counting).
3631 void identify_geometric_data(std::set<Data*>& geometric_data_pt)
3632 {
3633 // Loop over the node update data and add to the set
3634 const unsigned n_node = this->nnode();
3635 for (unsigned n = 0; n < n_node; n++)
3636 {
3637 geometric_data_pt.insert(
3638 dynamic_cast<SolidNode*>(this->node_pt(n))->variable_position_pt());
3639 }
3640 }

3731 /// Compute the geometric shape functions and also first
3732 /// and second derivatives w.r.t. Lagrangian coordinates at
3733 /// local coordinate s;
3734 /// Returns Jacobian of mapping from Lagrangian to local coordinates.
3735 /// Numbering:
3736 /// \b 1D:
3737 /// d2pidxi(i,0) = \f$ d^2 \psi_j / d \xi^2 \f$
3738 /// \b 2D:
3739 /// d2psidxi(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_0^2 \f$
3740 /// d2psidxi(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_1^2 \f$
3741 /// d2psidxi(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_1
3742 /// \f$
3743 /// \b 3D:
3744 /// d2psidxi(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_0^2 \f$
3745 /// d2psidxi(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_1^2 \f$
3746 /// d2psidxi(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_2^2 \f$
3747 /// d2psidxi(i,3) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_1 \f$
3748 /// d2psidxi(i,4) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_2 \f$
3749 /// d2psidxi(i,5) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_1 \partial \xi_2 \f$
3750 double d2shape_lagrangian(const Vector<double>& s,
3751 Shape& psi,
3752 DShape& dpsidxi,
3753 DShape& d2psidxi) const;

3760 /// \b 1D:
3761 /// d2pidxi(i,0) = \f$ d^2 \psi_j / d^2 \xi^2 \f$
3762 /// \b 2D:
3763 /// d2psidxi(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial^2 \xi_0^2 \f$
3764 /// d2psidxi(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial^2 \xi_1^2 \f$
3765 /// d2psidxi(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_1 \f$
3766 /// \b 3D:
3767 /// d2psidxi(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial^2 \xi_0^2 \f$
3768 /// d2psidxi(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial^2 \xi_1^2 \f$
3769 /// d2psidxi(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial^2 \xi_2^2 \f$

4003 /// Compute the residuals for the setup of an initial condition.
4004 /// The global equations are:
4005 /// \f[
4006 /// 0 = \int \left( \sum_{j=1}^N \sum_{k=1}^K X_{ijk} \psi_{jk}(\xi_n)
4007 /// - \frac{\partial^D R^{(IC)}_i(\xi_n)}{\partial t^D}
4008 /// \right) \psi_{lm}(\xi_n) \ dv
4009 /// \mbox{ \ \ \ \ for \ \ \ $l=1,...,N, \ \ m=1,...,K$}
4010 /// \f]
4011 /// where \f$ N \f$ is the number of nodes in the mesh and \f$ K \f$
4012 /// the number of generalised nodal coordinates. The initial shape
4013 /// of the solid body, \f$ {\bf R}^{(IC)},\f$ and its time-derivatives
4014 /// are specified via the \c GeomObject that is stored in the
4015 /// \c SolidFiniteElement::SolidInitialCondition object. The latter also
4016 /// stores the order of the time-derivative \f$ D \f$ to be assigned.
4017 virtual void get_residuals_for_solid_ic(Vector<double>& residuals)
4018 {
4019 residuals.initialise(0.0);
4020 fill_in_residuals_for_solid_ic(residuals);
4021 }
4022
4023 /// Fill in the residuals for the setup of an initial condition.
4024 /// The global equations are:
4025 /// \f[
4026 /// 0 = \int \left( \sum_{j=1}^N \sum_{k=1}^K X_{ijk} \psi_{jk}(\xi_n)
4027 /// - \frac{\partial^D R^{(IC)}_i(\xi_n)}{\partial t^D}
4028 /// \right) \psi_{lm}(\xi_n) \ dv
4029 /// \mbox{ \ \ \ \ for \ \ \ $l=1,...,N, \ \ m=1,...,K$}
4030 /// \f]
4031 /// where \f$ N \f$ is the number of nodes in the mesh and \f$ K \f$
4032 /// the number of generalised nodal coordinates. The initial shape
4033 /// of the solid body, \f$ {\bf R}^{(IC)},\f$ and its time-derivatives
4034 /// are specified via the \c GeomObject that is stored in the
4035 /// \c SolidFiniteElement::SolidInitialCondition object. The latter also
4036 /// stores the order of the time-derivative \f$ D \f$ to be assigned.
4037 void fill_in_residuals_for_solid_ic(Vector<double>& residuals)
4038 {
4039 // Call the generic residuals function with flag set to 0
4040 // using a dummy matrix argument
4041 fill_in_generic_jacobian_for_solid_ic(
4042 residuals, GeneralisedElement::Dummy_matrix, 0);
4043 }

4045 /// Fill in the residuals and Jacobian for the setup of an
4046 /// initial condition. The global equations are:
4047 /// \f[
4048 /// 0 = \int \left( \sum_{j=1}^N \sum_{k=1}^K X_{ijk} \psi_{jk}(\xi_n)
4049 /// - \frac{\partial^D R^{(IC)}_i(\xi_n)}{\partial t^D}
4050 /// \right) \psi_{lm}(\xi_n) \ dv
4051 /// \mbox{ \ \ \ \ for \ \ \ $l=1,...,N, \ \ m=1,...,K$}
4052 /// \f]
4053 /// where \f$ N \f$ is the number of nodes in the mesh and \f$ K \f$
4054 /// the number of generalised nodal coordinates. The initial shape
4055 /// of the solid body, \f$ {\bf R}^{(IC)},\f$ and its time-derivatives
4056 /// are specified via the \c GeomObject that is stored in the
4057 /// \c SolidFiniteElement::SolidInitialCondition object. The latter also
4058 /// stores the order of the time-derivative \f$ D \f$ to be assigned.
4059 void fill_in_jacobian_for_solid_ic(Vector<double>& residuals,
4060 DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian)
4061 {
4062 // Call the generic routine with the flag set to 1
4063 fill_in_generic_jacobian_for_solid_ic(residuals, jacobian, 1);
4064 }

4162 /// Access function that returns the local equation number that
4163 /// corresponds to the j-th coordinate of the k-th position-type at the
4164 /// n-th local node.
4165 inline int position_local_eqn(const unsigned& n,
4166 const unsigned& k,
4167 const unsigned& j) const
4168 {
4169#ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
4170 std::ostringstream error_message;
4171 bool error = false;
4172 if (n >= nnode())
4173 {
4174 error = true;
4175 error_message << "Range Error: Nodal number " << n
4176 << " is not in the range (0," << nnode() << ")";
4177 }
4178
4179 if (k >= nnodal_position_type())
4180 {
4181 error = true;
4182 error_message << "Range Error: Position type " << k
4183 << " is not in the range (0," << nnodal_position_type()
4184 << ")";
4185 }
4186
4187 if (j >= nodal_dimension())
4188 {
4189 error = true;
4190 error_message << "Range Error: Nodal coordinate " << j
4191 << " is not in the range (0," << nodal_dimension() << ")";
4192 }
4193
4194 if (error)
4195 {
4196 // Throw the error
4197 throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
4198 OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
4199 OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
4200 }
4201#endif
4202
4203 // Return the value
4204 return Position_local_eqn[(n * nnodal_position_type() + k) *
4205 nodal_dimension() +
4206 j];

4210 /// Overload the fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian() function to
4211 /// use finite
4212 /// differences to calculate the solid residuals by default
4213 void fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian(Vector<double>& residuals,
4214 DenseMatrix<double>& jacobian)
4215 {
4216 // Add the contribution to the residuals
4217 fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(residuals);
4218
4219 // Solve for the consistent acceleration in Newmark scheme?
4220 if (Solve_for_consistent_newmark_accel_flag)
4221 {

4223 return;
4224 }

4230 get_residuals(full_residuals);

4232 fill_in_jacobian_from_solid_position_by_fd(full_residuals, jacobian);

4239 // There could also be nodal data
4240 fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(full_residuals, jacobian);

4352 //========================================================================
4353 /// FaceElements are elements that coincide with the faces of
4354 /// higher-dimensional "bulk" elements. They are used on
4355 /// boundaries where additional non-trivial boundary conditions need to be
4356 /// applied. Examples include free surfaces, and applied traction conditions.
4357 /// In many cases, FaceElements need to evaluate to quantities
4358 /// in the associated bulk elements. For instance, the evaluation
4359 /// of a shear stresses on 2D FaceElement requires the evaluation
4360 /// of velocity derivatives in the associated 3D volume element etc.
4361 /// Therefore we store a pointer to the associated bulk element,
4362 /// and information about the relation between the local
4363 /// coordinates in the face and bulk elements.
4364 //========================================================================
4365 class FaceElement : public virtual FiniteElement
4366 {
4367 /// Typedef for the function that translates the face coordinate
4368 /// to the coordinate in the bulk element
4369 typedef void (*CoordinateMappingFctPt)(const Vector<double>& s,
4370 Vector<double>& s_bulk);
4371
4372 /// Typedef for the function that returns the partial derivative
4373 /// of the local coordinates in the bulk element
4374 /// with respect to the coordinates along the face.
4375 /// In addition this function returns an index of one of the
4376 /// bulk local coordinates that varies away from the edge
4377 typedef void (*BulkCoordinateDerivativesFctPt)(
4378 const Vector<double>& s,
4379 DenseMatrix<double>& ds_bulk_dsface,
4380 unsigned& interior_direction);
4381
4382 private:
4383 /// Pointer to a function that translates the face coordinate
4384 /// to the coordinate in the bulk element
4385 CoordinateMappingFctPt Face_to_bulk_coordinate_fct_pt;
4386
4387 /// Pointer to a function that returns the derivatives of the local
4388 /// "bulk" coordinates with respect to the local face coordinates.
4389 BulkCoordinateDerivativesFctPt Bulk_coordinate_derivatives_fct_pt;

4893 /// Provide additional storage for a specified number of
4894 /// values at the nodes of the FaceElement. (This is needed, for
4895 /// instance, in free-surface elements, if the non-penetration
4896 /// condition is imposed by Lagrange multipliers whose values
4897 /// are only stored at the surface nodes but not in the interior of
4898 /// the bulk element). \c nadditional_data_values[n] specifies the
4899 /// number of additional values required at node \c n of the
4900 /// FaceElement. \b Note: Since this function is executed separately
4901 /// for each FaceElement, nodes that are common to multiple elements
4902 /// might be resized repeatedly. To avoid this, we only allow
4903 /// a single resize operation by comparing the number of values stored
4904 /// at each node to the number of values the node had when it
4905 /// was simply a member of the associated "bulk"
4906 /// element. <b>There are cases where this will break!</b> -- e.g. if
4907 /// a node is common to two FaceElements which require
4908 /// additional storage for distinct quantities. Such cases
4909 /// need to be handled by "hand-crafted" face elements.
4910 void resize_nodes(Vector<unsigned>& nadditional_data_values)
4911 {
4912 // Locally cache the number of node
4913 unsigned n_node = nnode();
4914 // Resize the storage for values at the nodes:
4915 for (unsigned l = 0; l < n_node; l++)
4916 {
4917 // Find number of values stored at the node
4918 unsigned Initial_Nvalue = node_pt(l)->nvalue();
4919 // Read out the number of additional values
4920 unsigned Nadditional = nadditional_data_values[l];
4921 // If the node has not already been resized, resize it
4922 if ((Initial_Nvalue == Nbulk_value[l]) && (Nadditional > 0))
4923 {
4924 // Resize the node according to the number of additional values
4925 node_pt(l)->resize(Nbulk_value[l] + Nadditional);
4926 }
4927 } // End of loop over nodes
4928 }
4929
4930 /// Output boundary coordinate zeta
4931 void output_zeta(std::ostream& outfile, const unsigned& nplot);

5071 {

5136 //======================================================================
5137 /// Basic-ified FaceElement, without any of the functionality of
5138 /// of actual FaceElements -- it's just a surface element of the
5139 /// same geometric type as the FaceGeometry associated with
5140 /// bulk element specified by the template parameter. The element
5141 /// can be used to represent boundaries without actually being
5142 /// attached to a bulk element. Used mainly during unstructured
5143 /// mesh generation.
5144 //======================================================================
5145 template<class ELEMENT>
5146 class FreeStandingFaceElement : public virtual FaceGeometry<ELEMENT>
5147 {
5148 public:
5149 /// Constructor
5150 FreeStandingFaceElement()
5151 : FaceGeometry<ELEMENT>(), Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh(0)
5152 {
5153 // Check whether things have been set
5154#ifdef PARANOID
5155 Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh_has_been_set = false;
5156#endif
5157 }
5158
5159 /// Access function for the boundary number in bulk mesh
5160 inline const unsigned& boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh() const
5161 {
5162 return Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh;
5163 }
5164
5165
5166 /// Set function for the boundary number in bulk mesh
5167 inline void set_boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh(const unsigned& b)
5168 {
5169 Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh = b;
5170#ifdef PARANOID
5171 Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh_has_been_set = true;
5172#endif
5173 }
5174
5175 /// In a FaceElement, the "global" intrinsic coordinate
5176 /// of the element along the boundary, when viewed as part of
5177 /// a compound geometric object is specified using the
5178 /// boundary coordinate defined by the mesh.
5179 /// Note: Boundary coordinates will have been set up when
5180 /// creating the underlying mesh, and their values will have
5181 /// been stored at the nodes.
5182 double zeta_nodal(const unsigned& n,
5183 const unsigned& k,
5184 const unsigned& i) const
5185 {
5186 // Vector in which to hold the intrinsic coordinate
5187 Vector<double> zeta(this->dim());
5188
5189 // Get the k-th generalised boundary coordinate at node n
5190 this->node_pt(n)->get_coordinates_on_boundary(
5191 Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh, k, zeta);
5192
5193 // Return the individual coordinate
5194 return zeta[i];
5195 }
5196
5197 protected:
5198 /// The boundary number in the bulk mesh to which this element is attached
5199 unsigned Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh;
5200
5201#ifdef PARANOID
5202
5203 /// Has the Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh been set? Only included if
5204 /// compiled with PARANOID switched on.
5205 bool Boundary_number_in_bulk_mesh_has_been_set;
5206
5207#endif
5208 };
